[[Image:AlabamaJubilee90.jpg|thumb|Spectators mingle with hot air balloons at the Alabama Jubilee circa 1990 while balloonists inflate their craft for the evening activities.]] {{Coord|34|34|26|N|86|56|16|W|type:event_region:US-AL|display=title}} The '''Alabama Jubilee Hot-Air Balloon Classic''' is held annually on Memorial Day weekend in [[Decatur, Alabama]]. Each year the Jubilee hosts about 60 local and national hot-air balloons at [[Point Mallard Park]].
Public admission is free of charge, and the weekend boasts many fun and exciting activities. Below a partial listing of events that are part of each year's Jubilee:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.alabamajubilee.net/| title = Alabama Jubilee Hot Air Balloon Classic | date = 2009 | publisher = Alabama Jubilee }}</ref>
* Fireworks Extravaganza * Antique Tractor Show * Classic Car Show * Arts and Crafts * Live Stage Entertainment * Children’s Area * Food and Merchandise Vendors
The Alabama Jubilee is unique in that it allows for the crowd of around 50,000 to mingle with pilots and crews, while 7-story tall balloons inflate and float overhead. The Alabama Jubilee Hot-Air Balloon Classic consists of three different balloon events:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://216.26.146.243/DecaturCVB/default.aspx?id=69 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530064050/http://216.26.146.243/DecaturCVB/default.aspx?id=69 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2011-05-30 |title=Alabama Jubilee Hot Air Balloon and Music Festival |date=2009 |publisher=Decatur-Morgan County Convention and Visitors Bureau }}</ref>
* A Hare & Hound Race * A Balloon Glow * A Circumnavigational Task * Tethered Balloon Rides
==History== [[File:Alabama Jubilee.jpg|thumb|left|Hot air balloons inflating at the 2005 Alabama Jubilee]] The Alabama Jubilee Hot-Air Balloon Classic, one of the oldest hot-air balloon races in the mid-South, started in [[Decatur, AL]] in 1978 with competition among 17 balloonists from [[Alabama]], [[Kentucky]], [[Ohio]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Mississippi]] and [[Louisiana]]. It was a showcase for the new Decatur balloon, one of the first to represent a city, and an event to kick off Alabama's tourism season. The Jubilee now draws about 60 pilots from 20 states for two days of friendly competition during the annual [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend.{{cn|date=November 2017}}
=="The Ballooning Capital of Alabama"== The continued popularity of the Alabama Jubilee prompted the Alabama Legislature to designate the City of [[Decatur, AL|Decatur]] as the “Ballooning Capital of [[Alabama]].”{{cn|date=November 2017}}
The Jubilee has been named a Top 20 Tourism Event in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]] for May by the [[Atlanta, GA|Atlanta]]-based [[Southeast Tourism Society]].{{cn|date=November 2017}}
==Location== The Alabama Jubilee is held on the grounds of [[Point Mallard Park]], a municipal recreation complex that offers a {{convert|35|acre|m2|sing=on}} water park featuring an aquatic center with a wave pool, [[Olympic-sized swimming pool]]s, [[lazy river]], and several [[water slide]]s, as well as tennis courts, ball fields, hiking trails, campground, 18-hole championship golf course, indoor ice skating rink and recreation center.{{cn|date=November 2017}}
==See also== * [[Decatur, Alabama]] * [[Hot air balloon festivals]] * [[Point Mallard Park]]
