{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox magazine | title = Shahrvand-e-Emrooz | image_file = | image_size = | image_caption = | editor = | editor_title = | frequency = Weekly | circulation = | category = [[Political journalism|Political magazine]] | company = | publisher = | founded = | firstdate = | finaldate= September 2011 | country =Iran | language = [[Persian language|Persian]] | website = | issn = | oclc = }}
'''''Shahrvand-e-Emrooz''''' (''Today’s Citizen'' in English)<ref name=fox>{{cite news|title=Iranian Paper Shut Down for Obama Cover|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/11/12/iranian-paper-shut-down-for-obama-cover/|accessdate=7 September 2014|work=Fox News|date=12 November 2008}}</ref> was a [[Persian-language]] [[weekly]] [[news magazine]] which was closed down in September 2011.
==History and profile== [[Mohammad Ghoochani]] served as the editor-in-chief of the weekly.<ref name=ber>{{cite web|title=Iran: "How to lose friends and alienate your own people"|url=http://www.e-ir.info/2009/07/10/iran-%E2%80%9Chow-to-lose-friends-and-alienate-your-own-people%E2%80%9D-2/|work=e-International Relations|accessdate=5 October 2013|author=Bernd Kaussler|date=10 July 2009}}</ref> The magazine, based in [[Tehran]], was a reformist publication<ref name=fox/><ref>{{cite web|title=Reformist Weekly Banned for Publishing Image of Ahmadinejad|url=http://www.iranhumanrights.org/tag/shahrvand-e-emrooz/|work=Iran Human Rights|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> and was Iranian version of ''[[TIME magazine]]''.<ref name=ber/> It published significant interviews with leading figures, including [[Hassan Rouhani]] in 2008 and [[Hassan Khomeini]], grandson of [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iran News Round Up|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/160453/iran-news-round/michael-rubin|work=National Review Online|accessdate=5 October 2013|author=Michael Rubin|date=17 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Khomeini's rebel grandchildren rock the vote|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/MID-01-310513.html|work=Asia Times Online|accessdate=5 October 2013|author=Helia Ighani|author2=Garrett Nada |date=31 May 2013}}</ref>
==Bans and closure== ''Shahrvand-e-Emrooz'' was first closed down when it published a picture of [[U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] and his daughter on the cover of its 8 November 2008 issue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Could Obama victory lead to Iran talks?|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2008/nov/12/ml-iran-obama-111208/all/?print|accessdate=5 October 2013|newspaper=San Diego Tribune|date=12 November 2008|author=Ali Akbar Dareini|author2=Sally Buzbee|agency=AP|location=Tehran - Cairo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Media Environment Guide: Iran|url=http://www.combatfilms.com/mediaoperations/Media%20Environment%20Guide%20Iran.pdf|accessdate=7 December 2013|newspaper=BBC Monitoring|date=30 July 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801201438/http://www.combatfilms.com/mediaoperations/Media%20Environment%20Guide%20Iran.pdf|archivedate=1 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The weekly was also shut down in June 2009 following the [[Iranian presidential election, 2009|presidential election]].<ref name=ber/> The magazine resumed on 2 July 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran shuts down 2 newspaper for criticizing Ahmadinejad|url=http://news.az/articles/43763/print|accessdate=27 February 2015|work=News. Az|date=6 September 2011}}</ref> but it was again closed down in September 2011 due to the publication of a digital picture which mocked former President [[Mahmoud Ahmedinejad]] and his confidant [[Esfandiar Rahim Mashaei]].<ref name=gua>{{cite news|title=Iran newspaper closed down amid row over Mahmoud Ahmadinejad satire|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/sep/06/iran-newspaper-closed-ahmadinejad-satire|accessdate=5 October 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 September 2011|author=Saeed Kamali Dehghan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Iran: Magazine closed down amid row over satirical image|url=http://www.indexoncensorship.org/tag/shahrvand-e-emrooz/|work=Index|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref>
